We need a candidate that can both get Democrats fired up to vote and win back the places that voted for Trump, and I<U+2019>m the only candidate who<U+2019>s done it. I need your support because this is about a lot more than one debate.

I agree with Chairman @TomPerez that every candidate has to demonstrate progress to make that stage. But if progress isn<U+2019>t what we<U+2019>ve been able to achieve in Montana, our Party<U+2019>s definition of progress needs to change.

These rules are not the standard our Party should be setting. If we're ever going to get beyond partisan gridlock and back to governing, we must include those who have done the hard work to get things done outside of Washington.

But the DNC<U+2019>s new debate rules threaten to keep us off the debate stage because I didn<U+2019>t get in earlier. The truth is if I ever had to choose again between campaigning for 100,000 donors and securing healthcare for 100,000 people; well, that<U+2019>s the easiest decision I<U+2019>ll ever make.
We had a job to do in Montana. And we did it.

I don<U+2019>t regret for a minute waiting so long to launch my campaign. Nothing is more important to me than the work we did to expand Medicaid, freeze college tuition, ban foreign money from state elections, and protect a woman<U+2019>s right to make her own healthcare decisions.

Here's how you win a Trump state: you show up, you listen, and you recognize that no matter who you vote for, folks generally want the same things in life. 

We can win in Trump states, and we can take our country back. https://t.co/jYnF2ChDIu

I believe this budget reflects not only my priorities as Governor, but more importantly, the priorities of the people of the great state of Montana.

In order to preserve the progress we<U+2019>ve made across the state, especially in rural communities, I<U+2019>m proposing to fully fund Medicaid expansion to continue healthcare for nearly 100,000 Montanans. There<U+2019>s too much at stake not to keep Medicaid expansion going in Montana.

I am proposing to make sustainable investments in critical infrastructure across our state - in urban and rural communities - essential to our continued economic growth and to creating a future for Montana that our kids can build their families and lives in.

I am proposing to expand our investment in high-quality, affordable preschool, to once again freeze college tuition in our university system, and to join every other state in offering need-based financial aid.

I expect the 2019 legislature to work with me on what, at their core, should not be partisan issues when it comes to our budget. And in addition to being fiscally sound, work with me to address issues and priorities Montanans care about.
Montanans understand the importance of leaving money in the bank for unexpected things that might come our way. It<U+2019>s not just good policy, it<U+2019>s the fiscally responsible thing to do.
Montanans are best served when we work together, regardless of political party, on a budget that is not only balanced, but also funds essential services Montanans expect.
I<U+2019>m optimistic that in Montana we can still be a shining example for the country of how our political system is supposed to work.
